node.text:
Spacesuits and Moon dust. 👨‍🚀 On this day in 1969, lunar module Eagle landed on the Moon and astronauts Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin took humanity's first steps on the lunar surface. During an extensive conservation of Neil Armstrong's Apollo 11 spacesuit, pictured here, we made sure to preserve the remaining Moon dust on the spacesuit. After their Moonwalk, Armstrong and Aldrin didn’t wipe Moon dust off their suits before getting into the LM and Armstrong remarked that they “look like chimney sweeps.” Learn more about the conservation of the spacesuit at the link in our bio.

node.text: Apollo 11 isn't the only Michael Collins mission celebrating an anniversary right now. 55 years ago this week, the Gemini 10 mission was taking place with astronauts Michael Collins and John Young. It was the first spaceflight to rendezvous with two different vehicles in orbit (Agena Target Vehicles 10 and 8). The Gemini 10 capsule docked with Agena 10, and Collins performed an EVA to travel to Agena 8.

node.text:
80 years ago today, the first class of Black aviation cadets who would become the Tuskegee Airmen began training at Tuskegee Army Air Field.
The Tuskegee Army Air Field became the vital center for training African Americans to fly fighter and bomber aircraft during World War II. Serving in the 99th Fighter Squadron and the 332nd Fighter Group, the Tuskegee Airmen made a pioneering contribution to the war and the subsequent drive to end racial segregation in the American armed forces. That first class of pilots graduated from the Advanced Flying School in 1942.

Today would have been the 100th birthday of spaceflight legend and American hero John Glenn. Glenn became the first American to orbit the Earth in Friendship 7 in 1962 and returned to space on board Space Shuttle Discovery in 1998, becoming the only Mercury astronaut to fly on the space shuttle.
Pictured here is his spacesuit from his Mercury mission in Friendship 7. #AirSpacePhoto Visit the link in our bio to learn more about the suit through close-up photography.

Handshake in space 👨‍🚀 🤝 👨‍🚀

On this day in 1975, a US Apollo spacecraft and USSR Soyuz rendezvoused in the first international human spaceflight mission: the Apollo-Soyuz Test Project. This resulted in two different kind of "handshakes": a docking between the Apollo and Soyuz spacecraft (recreation pictured in image 1) and a good old-fashioned handshake between American astronaut Tom Stafford and Soviet cosmonaut Aleksei Leonov shaking hands (pictured in image 2).

node.text:
Yes, someone once did a barrel roll in this jet airliner.
The Boeing 367-80, better known as the Dash 80, revolutionized commercial air transportation when its developed version entered service as the famous Boeing 707, America's first jet airliner. Upon the Dash 80's first flight on this day in 1954, Boeing clearly had a winner. Flying 100 miles per hour faster than the de Havilland Comet and significantly larger, the new Boeing had a maximum range of more than 3,500 miles.
Boeing quickly turned its attention to selling the airline industry on this new jet transport. Clearly the industry was impressed with the capabilities of the prototype 707 but never more so than at the Gold Cup hydroplane races held on Lake Washington in Seattle, in August 1955. During a flypast of the new Dash 80, to the audience's intense delight and Boeing's profound shock, test pilot Alvin "Tex" Johnston barrel-rolled the Dash 80 over the lake in full view of thousands of astonished spectators. Johnston vividly displayed the superior strength and performance of this new jet, readily convincing the airline industry to buy this new airliner.
The Dash 80 is on display at the Udvar-Hazy Center in Virginia.

Pluto Flyby.
Today in 2015, the New Horizons spacecraft made its closest approach to the dwarf planet Pluto. Pictured here the highest-resolution color departure shot of Pluto's receding crescent from New Horizons. It was taken when the spacecraft was 120,000 miles (200,000 kilometers) away from Pluto.

Discovery v Woodpeckers

STS-70 launched today in 1995 but it wasn’t the original date for the flight. Space Shuttle Discovery faced a multi-week delay caused by Northern Flicker woodpeckers at Pad 39B who poked about 200 holes in the foam insulation of Discovery's external tank.

node.text:
Ike in flight 🚁
On this day in 1957, Dwight D. Eisenhower became the first president to fly in a helicopter while in office. That day, Air Force Maj. Joseph Barrett lifted off in this Bell H-13J (now on display at the Udvar-Hazy Center) with Eisenhower sitting in the right rear and James Rowley, chief of the White House Secret Service detail, sitting to his left on a simulated nuclear alert staged to test how quickly the Chief Executive and other government officials could depart Washington, DC, and reach a safe haven outside the city.
The H-13J (also called the Bell Ranger) was selected for this presidential first because it had an outstanding safety record and was the most reliable design available. It had an effective range of a mere 150 miles and was somewhat slow, with a top speed of around 100 miles per hours. Read more in the blog "Ike and the First Presidential Helicopters" at the link in our bio. #AirSpacePhoto

node.text:
"Ground Control to Major Tom"

On July 11, 1969 – only 5 days before Neil Armstrong, Michael Collins, and Buzz Aldrin set out on their journey to the Moon – a relatively unknown British musician named David Bowie released a single titled "Space Oddity." The timing was no coincidence. Bowie had written the song after being inspired by Stanley Kubrick’s 1968 film “2001: A Space Odyssey.” In his mind, it had little to do with the American space program, but Bowie’s record label saw an opportunity to tap into the Apollo excitement and so rushed the song’s release ahead of the album for which it would be the opening track. The song caught the attention of the BBC, who approached Bowie about using the song during their coverage of the lunar landing.
